By Cod. 4. 21. 17 Justinian made it the measure ofa penalty to be paid (additional, in unwritten contracts of sale, to specilic performance ordamages as assessed by the judge) by the party whorefused to executa. Mr. Hunter (Roman Law p. 332) seems clearly to be wrong in supposing that in a sale which the parties had not agreed to reduce to writing the defaulter could escape scot free by forfeiting the arra which he had given, or double that which he had received. He was subject to the ordinary rule, and was bound from the moment the price was agreed upon to do what he had promised. The effect of Justinian’s other change was that, where the parties had agreed to reduce the contract to writing, there was a locus poenitentiae, and therefore no obligatio, until the document had been formally completed as required in this section, even though the terrns and the price had been settled ; but that if, in such a case, arra had been given, and either party repudiated, he must, if purchaser, forfeit tris arra, arrd, if vendor, pay arr equivalent sum besides returning it.
